Note: ================================================================
Note: Common Code Generation Utilities
Note: ================================================================
Note: Universal code generation utilities used by all backend translators.
Note: Provides output buffering, indentation management, and error tracking.
Note: Used by 51+ backend translators (HIR → Target Language).
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ================================================================
Note: Code Generation Context Type
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
51+ HIR-to-target backends all need the same emission scaffolding: output
buffer, indent tracking, position tracking for diagnostics, error/warning
lists, and a metadata slot for backend-private state. Centralizing the layout
here lets a backend pick up the full feature set by passing the context handle
through its emitters rather than reinventing buffer plumbing.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
72-byte heap layout. Fixed offsets (used by every accessor): output@0,
indent_level@8, indent_string@16, current_line@24, current_column@32,
errors@40, warnings@48, has_error@56, metadata@64. Reordering ANY field breaks
every backend in the tree; treat this as a stable ABI.
@End Implementation
Type called "CodeGenerationContext":
    output as String
    indent_level as Integer
    indent_string as String
    current_line as Integer
    current_column as Integer
    errors as Integer
    warnings as Integer
    has_error as Integer
    metadata as Integer
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: Context Creation and Destruction
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
A factory rather than per-field construction is used because the context has
nine fields with non-trivial defaults: empty output, level-0 indent, four-space
indent string (the conventional default), 1-based line/column counters,
fresh error/warning lists, and zeroed has_error/metadata. Backends that need a
different indent style call create_code_context_with_indent instead.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Allocates 72 bytes via Layout, then writes each field by absolute offset.
Allocation failure surfaces as a 0 return so callers can check without
exceptions. Lines and columns start at 1 (not 0) to match human-readable
diagnostic conventions.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_code_context" that takes nothing returns Integer:
    Let context_size be 72
    Let context be proc allocate from Layout with context_size

    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize output buffer (a Runa String is a NUL-terminated pointer)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 0, ""

    Note: Initialize indentation (level 0, 4 spaces default)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 16, "    "

    Note: Initialize line/column tracking
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 24, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 32, 1

    Note: Initialize error and warning lists
    Let errors be proc create from List
    Let warnings be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 40, errors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 48, warnings

    Note: Initialize error flag
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 56, 0

    Note: Initialize metadata dictionary (for backend-specific data)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 64, 0

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning:
Some target languages have strong house style (Python: 4 spaces; Go: tab; Lisp:
2 spaces). Letting the backend pick the indent unit up front avoids every
backend having to call set_indent_string immediately after creation.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Builds on create_code_context then overwrites offset 16. The custom string is
not validated; passing a non-whitespace string would produce visible artifacts
but no error.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_code_context_with_indent" that takes indent_string as String returns Integer:
    Let context be proc create_code_context

    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Override default indent string
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 16, indent_string

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning:
The 72-byte block, errors list, and warnings list are owned by the caller's
allocator (the driver passes them through to its arena/ARC strategy of
choice). Releasing them here would double-free; this routine therefore exists
only as a contract endpoint so backends can call "destroy" without thinking
about ownership.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Null-checks the input and returns 1 on success. The actual memory release is
the caller's responsibility per Runa's five-tier memory model.
@End Implementation
Process called "destroy_code_context" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Context memory will be freed by caller
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Output Emission
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The fundamental write primitive: append to output and advance the column
counter. Column tracking is char-count based (length of the appended String),
which matches what diagnostics want for byte-oriented targets but is
approximate for variable-width Unicode (acceptable here because emitted code
is typically ASCII).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
1. Read current output at offset 0.
2. Concat with the new text via StringCore.
3. Write back to offset 0.
4. Read column at offset 32, add text length, write back.
Note: this is NOT line-aware - newlines inside `text` will desync column
tracking. Callers that emit newlines should prefer emit_line.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints:
Repeated concat is O(n^2) in total emitted bytes. For multi-megabyte outputs,
either pre-buffer or switch to a chunk-list builder; both are out-of-scope here
since this module is a hot path for many backends.
@End Performance_Hints
Process called "emit" that takes context as Integer, text as String returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get current output
    Let current_output be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    Note: Append text
    Let new_output be proc string_concat from StringPrim with current_output, text

    Note: Update output
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 0, new_output

    Note: Update column tracking
    Let text_length be proc string_length from StringCore with text
    Let current_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 32, current_column plus text_length

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A single emit-then-newline helper centralizes the line/column bookkeeping that
plain emit cannot do (incrementing line, resetting column to 1). All
indent-aware emitters terminate lines through this routine so position state
stays consistent.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits text via emit (which advances column), emits "\n" via emit (which
desyncs column briefly), then explicitly fixes line up by one and column back
to 1. The intermediate emit of "\n" is acceptable because the explicit fixups
that follow it overwrite the broken column.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_line" that takes context as Integer, text as String returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Emit text
    proc emit with context, text

    Note: Emit newline
    proc emit with context, "\n"

    Note: Update line tracking
    Let current_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 24, current_line plus 1

    Note: Reset column to 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 32, 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Common enough to deserve a named alias rather than `emit_line(ctx, "")`.
Reads clearer at call sites and lets future implementations specialize the
empty-text case without touching every caller.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Forwards to emit_line with the empty string, which still triggers the line
counter increment and column reset.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_newline" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit_line with context, ""
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Indentation Management
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Indentation is emitted as N copies of the stored indent_string, not as
indent_level multiplied into a precomputed buffer. This avoids cache effects
from per-context indent strings of varying widths and keeps the implementation
allocator-free aside from the underlying string concat.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read indent_level from offset 8, indent_string from offset 16, then loop
indent_level times calling emit. The loop runs once for each indent stop, not
once per character.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_indent" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8
    Let indent_string be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 16

    Note: Emit indent_string for each indent level
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than indent_level:
        proc emit with context, indent_string
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A dedicated helper instead of inline increment keeps the indent_level offset
(8) constant in one place. Backends call this when entering a nested scope,
paired with decrease_indent on exit; the pairing discipline is enforced by
convention rather than by an indent stack.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read offset 8, add 1, write back. No upper-bound clamp; deeply pathological
indentation would just produce very wide output, never overflow.
@End Implementation
Process called "increase_indent" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, current_level plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Underflow protection (clamp at zero) is included here, unlike the Verilog
backend's indent_dec, because this routine is the shared infrastructure used
by 50+ backends; a single mismatched increase/decrease pair in one backend
must not corrupt all downstream emission.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read offset 8; only decrement if greater than 0. Silent saturation rather
than an error because diagnosing a malformed indent stack from inside a code
emitter is not actionable in production.
@End Implementation
Process called "decrease_indent" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    Note: Prevent negative indentation
    If current_level is greater than 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, current_level minus 1
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Direct level setting (as opposed to inc/dec only) supports backends that want
to snapshot and restore the indent (e.g., for emitting an inline expression
inside a deeply indented context). Negative inputs are clamped to zero with
the same rationale as decrease_indent.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Branches on sign of `level`. Non-negative values are stored verbatim;
negatives become 0 so the indent state stays consistent regardless of caller
arithmetic mistakes.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_indent_level" that takes context as Integer, level as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Prevent negative indentation
    If level is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, 0
    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, level
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Read-only accessor so backends needing to checkpoint and restore the indent
level (e.g., emit a deeply nested expression then return) don't have to know
the offset 8 contract.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Direct memory read from offset 8; returns 0 on null context to remain safe in
"defensive" emission paths.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_indent_level" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
A late-binding alternative to create_code_context_with_indent for backends
that compute their indent style after context creation (e.g., from a project
config file read mid-pipeline).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Overwrites offset 16. The previously stored String is left for the allocator
to reclaim per the project's memory model.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_indent_string" that takes context as Integer, indent_string as String returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 16, indent_string

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the conventional four-space default on null context so callers can
unconditionally use the result for cosmetic purposes (e.g., embedded snippets)
without a separate null guard.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Reads offset 16. The "    " (four spaces) fallback matches the default set in
create_code_context, keeping behavior consistent on the error path.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_indent_string" that takes context as Integer returns String:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return "    "
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 16
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Indented Block Helpers
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The dominant emission shape across backends - indent then text then newline -
is consolidated into one call so the indent-then-emit-then-newline pattern is
not duplicated 50+ times in the codebase.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Calls emit_indent, then emit_line. Two separate primitive calls rather than
a fused implementation so behavior stays composable.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_indented_line" that takes context as Integer, text as String returns Integer:
    proc emit_indent with context
    proc emit_line with context, text
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Companion to emit_indented_line for cases that need to follow the text with
additional inline content before terminating the line (e.g., emit "func "
then a parameter list then ";").
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Indent then emit, with NO trailing newline; the caller controls when the
current line ends.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_indented" that takes context as Integer, text as String returns Integer:
    proc emit_indent with context
    proc emit with context, text
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Semantic alias for increase_indent that reads better at backend call sites
opening a block, parallel to end_indented_block on exit.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
One-line delegation to increase_indent.
@End Implementation
Process called "begin_indented_block" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    proc increase_indent with context
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Semantic alias for decrease_indent paired with begin_indented_block. Inherits
the underflow protection from decrease_indent.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
One-line delegation to decrease_indent.
@End Implementation
Process called "end_indented_block" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    proc decrease_indent with context
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Output Retrieval
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Final-result retrieval for the driver. Returns the empty string on null
context so the caller can blindly write it to disk without crashing on an
error path.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Reads offset 0. The String is shared by reference, not copied; if the caller
intends to mutate the context further the result should be copied first.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_output" that takes context as Integer returns String:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Length lookup without materializing the String at the call site is useful for
size-budget checks (e.g., warn if the emitted file exceeds a target size) and
for delta computations between emission phases.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Composes get_output and StringCore length. The intermediate String reference
costs nothing extra because it is the same handle stored at offset 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_output_length" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let output be proc get_output with context
    Return proc string_length from StringCore with output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reset for multi-pass backends that emit, validate, then re-emit with
adjustments. Errors and warnings are intentionally NOT cleared so accumulated
diagnostics survive a content reset, matching the typical "retry emission
after rejecting partial result" workflow.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Zeroes the output String and resets line/column to 1. Indent level, indent
string, error list, warning list, has_error flag, and metadata are left
untouched.
@End Implementation
Process called "clear_output" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 0, ""
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 24, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 32, 1

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Position Tracking
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
1-based position accessor for diagnostics. Returning 1 (not 0) on null context
keeps downstream "Error at L:C" formatters from producing the visually
suspicious "Error at 0:0" message.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Direct read of offset 24.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_current_line" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pair of get_current_line; same null-context fallback rationale.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Direct read of offset 32. Tracks chars since last newline as advanced by emit.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_current_column" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 32
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Error and Warning Management
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Errors and warnings are kept in separate lists because callers (drivers, IDE
servers) frequently need to render them with different severities and counts.
Setting the has_error flag in addition to the list lets a fast check
("did anything fail?") skip the list-size traversal.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Append the message to the error list at offset 40 and set has_error at
offset 56 to 1. The flag is idempotent (multiple errors still leave it at 1).
@End Implementation
Process called "add_generation_error" that takes context as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get error list
    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 40

    Note: Add error message
    proc append from List with errors, message

    Note: Set error flag
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 56, 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Codifies the "Error at L:C: message" prefix once so every backend gets
uniform error formatting. Diagnostic consumers (IDEs, log parsers) can rely
on the prefix shape.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Builds the prefix by chained concat, then delegates to add_generation_error
which handles list append and flag setting.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_generation_error_with_location" that takes context as Integer, message as String, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Format error with location
    Let line_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line
    Let col_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with column

    Let formatted be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Error at ", line_str
    Set formatted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with formatted, ":"
    Set formatted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with formatted, col_str
    Set formatted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with formatted, ": "
    Set formatted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with formatted, message

    Return proc add_generation_error with context, formatted
End Process

@Reasoning:
Warnings DO NOT set has_error; this is the central reason for keeping
add_generation_warning and add_generation_error as distinct routines. A
warning-only run should still be considered successful by has_errors callers.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Single append to the warning list at offset 48. has_error at offset 56 stays
unchanged.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_generation_warning" that takes context as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get warning list
    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 48

    Note: Add warning message
    proc append from List with warnings, message

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mirror of add_generation_error_with_location for warnings; keeps the prefix
shape ("Warning at L:C: ...") symmetric and parser-friendly.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Builds the prefix by chained concat and delegates to add_generation_warning.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_generation_warning_with_location" that takes context as Integer, message as String, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Format warning with location
    Let line_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line
    Let col_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with column

    Let formatted be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Warning at ", line_str
    Set formatted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with formatted, ":"
    Set formatted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with formatted, col_str
    Set formatted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with formatted, ": "
    Set formatted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with formatted, message

    Return proc add_generation_warning with context, formatted
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exposes the raw list handle so drivers can iterate, format, and print
diagnostics without copying. Caller MUST treat the returned handle as
read-only; mutating it would corrupt the context's view of error state.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Direct read of offset 40. Returns 0 (null handle) on null context.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_errors" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 40
End Process

@Reasoning:
Companion to get_errors; same caller contract (read-only view).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Direct read of offset 48.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_warnings" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 48
End Process

@Reasoning:
The boolean flag exists precisely so this question doesn't require an O(n)
list traversal; it's checked frequently by emission decision branches that
want to bail early on a failed backend.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Direct read of offset 56. 0 = clean, non-zero = at least one error logged.
@End Implementation
Process called "has_errors" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 56
End Process

@Reasoning:
Distinct from has_errors because some consumers (test runners, summaries)
report total error count. Computed on demand to avoid maintaining a second
counter that could drift from the list size.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Reads list handle from offset 40, calls List.size. O(1) since List tracks
its size internally.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_error_count" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 40
    Return proc size from List with errors
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mirror of get_error_count for warnings. Kept separate so summary lines
can read "N errors, M warnings" without a custom enumerator.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Reads list handle from offset 48 and calls List.size.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_warning_count" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 48
    Return proc size from List with warnings
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Metadata Storage (Backend-Specific Data)
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The metadata slot is an opaque integer (typically a pointer) where each
backend stows its private state - symbol tables, import maps, label
counters, etc. - without polluting the shared CodeGenerationContext schema.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Single write to offset 64. The value is uninterpreted; backends are
responsible for the lifetime of whatever they store there.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_metadata" that takes context as Integer, metadata as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 64, metadata

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Read-side of the metadata slot. Returns 0 on null context so backends can
unconditionally call get_metadata and then check the result rather than
checking the context first.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Direct read of offset 64.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_metadata" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 64
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Convenience Helpers
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Named alias for emit clarifies intent when the call site wants to make the
"this is a delimiter between items" structure visible in code.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Pass-through to emit.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_separator" that takes context as Integer, separator as String returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, separator
End Process

@Reasoning:
Frequent enough across backends that a named helper avoids string-literal
duplication (" " or " " in many places) and gives a single point to swap
for non-breaking spaces if a target ever requires that.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits a single ASCII space.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_space" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, " "
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tight `,` (no trailing space) used when the caller manages spacing
independently, e.g. between consecutive tokens in compact emission modes.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits a single comma.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_comma" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, ","
End Process

@Reasoning:
Statement-terminator helper for C-family targets. Backends that don't use
semicolons (Python, ML) simply don't call it.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits a single semicolon.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_semicolon" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, ";"
End Process

@Reasoning:
`, ` with trailing space is the dominant inter-item separator in
comma-separated lists. Splitting from emit_comma keeps the trailing-space
choice in one place per target.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits comma followed by space.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_comma_separator" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, ", "
End Process

@Reasoning:
C-family block-opener. Named helpers (vs. raw emit) make the structural intent
obvious at call sites and make grep for "where do we start a brace block"
trivial.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits `{`. No indent change here; see begin_block for the indent-aware variant.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_opening_brace" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, "{"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counterpart to emit_opening_brace; same naming rationale.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits `}`.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_closing_brace" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, "}"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Index/subscript opener for C/Java/Rust/Python-style array access.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits `[`.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_opening_bracket" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, "["
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counterpart to emit_opening_bracket.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits `]`.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_closing_bracket" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, "]"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Argument-list and grouping-expression opener for most curly/braced languages.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits `(`.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_opening_paren" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, "("
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counterpart to emit_opening_paren.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits `)`.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_closing_paren" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emit with context, ")"
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Block Generation Helpers
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The "block scaffolding" pattern is a fused emit+indent so callers always pair
the opener with the indent push, eliminating the bug class where one is
forgotten and child statements emit at the parent's column.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
emit_line for the opener (e.g. "{") followed by increase_indent. The opener
goes on its own line so brace style is "Allman" by default; backends wanting
K&R style emit the opener manually before calling increase_indent.
@End Implementation
Process called "begin_block" that takes context as Integer, opening as String returns Integer:
    proc emit_line with context, opening
    proc increase_indent with context
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric counterpart to begin_block: decrease indent first so the closing
token aligns at the parent scope's column, then emit it on its own line.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
decrease_indent then emit_indented_line with the closing token (e.g. "}").
@End Implementation
Process called "end_block" that takes context as Integer, closing as String returns Integer:
    proc decrease_indent with context
    proc emit_indented_line with context, closing
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Named alias for the C-family brace case, the dominant block form across the
backends in this tree.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegates to begin_block with "{".
@End Implementation
Process called "begin_brace_block" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc begin_block with context, "{"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counterpart to begin_brace_block.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegates to end_block with "}".
@End Implementation
Process called "end_brace_block" that takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc end_block with context, "}"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Convenience for emitting a single statement string at the current indent on
its own line, the most common shape inside a block body.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegates to emit_indented_line.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_block_statement" that takes context as Integer, statement as String returns Integer:
    proc emit_indented_line with context, statement
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: List Generation Helpers
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Inline (single-line) list-item helper that takes the is_last flag at the call
site so the separator is added if and only if more items follow. This removes
the trailing-comma bug class from per-backend list emitters.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emit item; if NOT last (is_last == 0) emit ", ". Backends are expected to
compute is_last as (index == count - 1) when iterating.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_list_item" that takes context as Integer, item as String, is_last as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit with context, item

    If is_last is equal to 0:
        proc emit_comma with context
        proc emit_space with context
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-line list form for cases where each item is emitted on its own indented
line (e.g., Python tuple literals or formatted argument lists). Uses comma
without space because the newline acts as the visual separator.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
emit_indented(item), then if not last emit ",", then unconditionally
emit_newline. The terminating newline runs even on the last item so the
closing bracket lands on a fresh line.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_list_item_with_newline" that takes context as Integer, item as String, is_last as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit_indented with context, item

    If is_last is equal to 0:
        proc emit with context, ","
    End If

    proc emit_newline with context

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Comment Generation Helpers
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The comment prefix is parameterized because different targets use different
markers (// for C-family, # for Python/shell, -- for Lua/SQL). Centralizing
the indent-prefix-space-text-newline shape ensures every backend's line
comments line up under the same column rules.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
emit_indented(prefix), emit_space, emit_line(text). The space between prefix
and text matches widely-used style guides.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_line_comment" that takes context as Integer, comment_prefix as String, text as String returns Integer:
    proc emit_indented with context, comment_prefix
    proc emit_space with context
    proc emit_line with context, text
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Block-comment scaffolding is broken into start/line/end helpers so
backend-specific decoration ("*" prefix on each interior line for C-style
JSDoc, for example) can be injected by the caller between start and end.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Emits the start prefix (e.g. "/*") on its own indented line.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_block_comment_start" that takes context as Integer, prefix as String returns Integer:
    proc emit_indented_line with context, prefix
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each interior comment line is emitted at the current indent. The caller is
responsible for prefixing per-line decoration ("* ") in the text argument; the
helper itself stays decoration-agnostic.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegates to emit_indented_line with the supplied text.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_block_comment_line" that takes context as Integer, text as String returns Integer:
    proc emit_indented_line with context, text
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric counterpart to emit_block_comment_start. Suffix is parameterized
to support "*/" (C-family) and ":End Note" (Runa-style) without two distinct
helpers.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegates to emit_indented_line with the supplied suffix.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_block_comment_end" that takes context as Integer, suffix as String returns Integer:
    proc emit_indented_line with context, suffix
    Return 1
End Process
